.TH inet 3 "kernel 10.6.1" "Ericsson AB" "Erlang Module Definition"
.SH NAME
inet \- Access to Network protocols.

.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
This module, together with \fIgen_tcp\fR, \fIgen_udp\fR and \fIgen_sctp\fR provides access to the Network protocols TCP, SCTP and UDP over IP, as well as stream and datagram protocols over the local (unix) address domain / protocol domain.

.PP
See also ERTS User's Guide: Inet Configuration or more information about how to configure an Erlang runtime system for IP communication.

.PP
The following four Kernel configuration parameters affect the behavior of all \fIgen_tcp\fR, \fIgen_udp\fR and \fIgen_sctp\fR sockets opened on an Erlang node:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIinet_default_connect_options\fR can contain a list of default options used for all sockets created by a \fIgen_tcp:connect/2,3,4\fR](\fIgen_tcp:connect/2\fR) call.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIinet_default_listen_options\fR can contain a list of default options used for sockets created by a \fIgen_tcp:listen/2\fR call.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIinet_default_udp_options\fR can contain a list of default options used for all sockets created by a \fIgen_udp:open/1,2\fR](\fIgen_udp:open/2\fR) call.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIinet_default_sctp_options\fR can contain a list of default options used for all sockets created by a \fIgen_sctp:open/0,1\fR](\fIgen_sctp:open/1\fR) call.

.RE

.PP
For the \fIgen_tcp:accept/1,2\fR call, the values of the listening socket options are inherited. Therefore there is no corresponding application variable for \fIaccept\fR.

.PP
Using the Kernel configuration parameters above, one can set default options for all TCP sockets on a node, but use this with care. Options such as \fI{delay_send,true}\fR can be specified in this way. The following is an example of starting an Erlang node with all sockets using delayed send:

.IP
.nf
$ erl -sname test -kernel \\
inet_default_connect_options '[{delay_send,true}]' \\
inet_default_listen_options '[{delay_send,true}]'

.fi

.PP
\fBPlease note\fR that the default option \fI{active, true}\fR cannot be changed, for internal implementation reasons.

.PP
Addresses as inputs to functions can be either a string or a tuple. For example, the IP address 150.236.20.73 can be passed to \fIgethostbyaddr/1\fR, either as a string \fI"150.236.20.73"\fR or as a tuple \fI{150, 236, 20, 73}\fR.

.PP
\fIIPv4 address examples:\fR

.IP
.nf
Address          ip_address()
-------          ------------
127.0.0.1        {127,0,0,1}
192.168.42.2     {192,168,42,2}

.fi

.PP
\fIIPv6 address examples:\fR

.IP
.nf
Address          ip_address()
-------          ------------
::1             {0,0,0,0,0,0,0,1}
::192.168.42.2  {0,0,0,0,0,0,(192 bsl 8) bor 168,(42 bsl 8) bor 2}
::FFFF:192.168.42.2
                {0,0,0,0,0,16#FFFF,(192 bsl 8) bor 168,(42 bsl 8) bor 2}
3ffe:b80:1f8d:2:204:acff:fe17:bf38
                {16#3ffe,16#b80,16#1f8d,16#2,16#204,16#acff,16#fe17,16#bf38}
fe80::204:acff:fe17:bf38
                {16#fe80,0,0,0,16#204,16#acff,16#fe17,16#bf38}

.fi

.PP
Function \fIparse_address/1\fR can be useful:

.IP
.nf
1> inet:parse_address("192.168.42.2").
{ok,{192,168,42,2}}
2> inet:parse_address("::FFFF:192.168.42.2").
{ok,{0,0,0,0,0,65535,49320,10754}}

.fi

