.SH DATA TYPES
.LP
.B
\fBaddress_family() :: inet | inet6 | local.\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBancillary_data() ::\fR
\fB          [{tos, byte()} | {tclass, byte()} | {ttl, byte()}].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Ancillary data / control messages.

.PP
Ancillary data received with a data packet, read with the socket option \fIpktoptions\fR from a TCP socket, or to set in a call to \fIgen_udp:send/4\fR or \fIgen_udp:send/5\fR.

.PP
The value(s) correspond to the currently active socket options \fIrecvtos\fR, \fIrecvtclass\fR and \fIrecvttl\fR, or for a single send operation the option(s) to override the currently active socket option(s).


.RE
.B
\fBether_address() :: [0..255].\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBfamily_address() ::\fR
\fB          inet_address() | inet6_address() | local_address().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
A general network address.

.PP
A general network address format of the form \fI{Family, Destination}\fR where \fIFamily\fR is an atom such as \fIlocal\fR and the format of \fIDestination\fR depends on \fIFamily\fR.  \fIDestination\fR is a complete address (for example an IP address with port number).


.RE
.B
\fBgetifaddrs_ifopts() ::\fR
\fB          [Ifopt ::\fR
\fB               {flags,\fR
\fB                Flags ::\fR
\fB                    [up | broadcast | loopback | pointtopoint |\fR
\fB                     running | multicast]} |\fR
\fB               {addr, Addr :: ip_address()} |\fR
\fB               {netmask, Netmask :: ip_address()} |\fR
\fB               {broadaddr, Broadaddr :: ip_address()} |\fR
\fB               {dstaddr, Dstaddr :: ip_address()} |\fR
\fB               {hwaddr, Hwaddr :: [byte()]}].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Interface address description list.

.PP
A list returned from \fIgetifaddrs/0,1\fR for a named interface, translated from the returned data of the POSIX API function \fIgetaddrinfo()\fR.

.PP
\fIHwaddr\fR is hardware dependent, for example, on Ethernet interfaces it is the 6-byte Ethernet address (MAC address (EUI-48 address)).

.PP
The tuples \fI{addr,Addr}\fR, \fI{netmask,Netmask}\fR, and possibly \fI{broadaddr,Broadaddr}\fR or \fI{dstaddr,Dstaddr}\fR are repeated in the list if the interface has got multiple addresses.  An interface may have multiple \fI{flag,_}\fR tuples for example if it has different flags for different address families.

.PP
Multiple \fI{hwaddr,Hwaddr}\fR tuples is hard to say anything definite about, though. The tuple \fI{flag,Flags}\fR is mandatory, all others are optional.

.PP
Do not rely too much on the order of \fIFlags\fR atoms or the \fIIfopt\fR tuples. There are however some rules:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fI{flag,_}\fR tuple applies to all other tuples that follow.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
Immediately after \fI{addr,_}\fR follows \fI{netmask,_}\fR.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
Immediately thereafter may \fI{broadaddr,_}\fR follow if \fIbroadcast\fR is member of \fIFlags\fR, or \fI{dstaddr,_}\fR if \fIpointtopoint\fR is member of \fIFlags\fR. Both \fI{dstaddr,_}\fR and \fI{broadaddr,_}\fR doesn't occur for the same \fI{addr,_}\fR.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
Any \fI{netmask,_}\fR, \fI{broadaddr,_}\fR, or \fI{dstaddr,_}\fR tuples that follow an \fI{addr,Addr}\fR tuple concerns the address \fIAddr\fR.

.RE

.PP
The tuple \fI{hwaddr,_}\fR is not returned on Solaris, as the hardware address historically belongs to the link layer and it is not returned by the Solaris API function \fIgetaddrinfo()\fR.

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fROn Windows, the data is fetched from different OS API functions, so the \fINetmask\fR and \fIBroadaddr\fR values may be calculated, just as some \fIFlags\fR values.



.RE
.B
\fBhostent() :: #hostent{}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
A record describing a host; name and address.

.PP
Corresponds to the \fIC\fR: \fIstruct hostent\fR as returned by for example \fIgethostbyname(3)\fR.

.PP
The record is defined in the Kernel include file \fI"inet.hrl"\fR.

.PP
Add the following directive to the module:

.IP
.nf
-include_lib("kernel/include/inet.hrl").

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBhostname() :: atom() | string().\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBi_option() ::\fR
\fB          port | module | recv | sent | owner | local_address |\fR
\fB          {local_address, ShowPorts :: boolean()} |\fR
\fB          foreign_address |\fR
\fB          {foreign_address, ShowPorts :: boolean()} |\fR
\fB          state | type.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Options for selecting statistics items.

.PP
Regarding \fIShowPorts\fR, see \fIshow_ports\fR as described in the \fIi/2\fR function, defaults to \fIfalse\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBinet6_address() ::\fR
\fB          {inet6, {ip6_address() | any | loopback, port_number()}}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
A network address for the \fIinet6\fR family (\fIAF_INET6\fR, IPv6)

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRThis address format is currently experimental and for completeness to make all address families have a \fI{Family, Destination}\fR representation.



.RE
.B
\fBinet_address() ::\fR
\fB          {inet, {ip4_address() | any | loopback, port_number()}}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
A network address for the \fIinet\fR family (\fIAF_INET\fR, IPv4)

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRThis address format is currently experimental and for completeness to make all address families have a \fI{Family, Destination}\fR representation.



.RE
.B
\fBinet_backend() :: {inet_backend, inet | socket}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Implementation backend selector for \fIsocket/0\fR.

.PP
Selects the implementation backend for sockets. The current default is \fIinet\fR which uses \fIinet_drv.c\fR to call the platform's socket API. The value \fIsocket\fR instead uses the \fIsocket\fR module and its NIF implementation.

.PP
This is a \fItemporary\fR option that will be ignored in a future release.


.RE
.B
\fBip4_address() :: {0..255, 0..255, 0..255, 0..255}.\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBip6_address() ::\fR
\fB          {0..65535,\fR
\fB           0..65535,\fR
\fB           0..65535,\fR
\fB           0..65535,\fR
\fB           0..65535,\fR
\fB           0..65535,\fR
\fB           0..65535,\fR
\fB           0..65535}.\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBip_address() :: ip4_address() | ip6_address().\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBlocal_address() :: {local, File :: binary() | string()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
A network address for the \fIlocal\fR family (\fIAF_LOCAL | AF_UNIX\fR)

.PP
This address family, also known as "Unix domain sockets" only works on Unix-like systems.

.PP
\fIFile\fR is normally a file pathname in a local filesystem. It is limited in length by the operating system, traditionally to 108 bytes.

.PP
A \fIbinary/0\fR is passed as is to the operating system, but a \fIstring/0\fR is encoded according to the system filename encoding mode.

.PP
Other addresses are possible, for example Linux implements "Abstract Addresses".  See the documentation for Unix Domain Sockets on your system, normally \fIunix\fR in manual section 7.

.PP
In most API functions where you can use this address family the port number must be \fI0\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBmodule_socket() ::\fR
\fB          {'$inet', Handler :: module(), Handle :: term()}.\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBport_number() :: 0..65535.\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBposix() ::\fR
\fB          eaddrinuse | eaddrnotavail | eafnosupport | ealready |\fR
\fB          econnaborted | econnrefused | econnreset | edestaddrreq |\fR
\fB          ehostdown | ehostunreach | einprogress | eisconn | emsgsize |\fR
\fB          enetdown | enetunreach | enopkg | enoprotoopt | enotconn |\fR
\fB          enotty | enotsock | eproto | eprotonosupport | eprototype |\fR
\fB          esocktnosupport | etimedout | ewouldblock | exbadport |\fR
\fB          exbadseq |\fR
\fB          file:posix().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
POSIX Error Code \fIatom/0\fR.

.PP
An atom that is named from the POSIX error codes used in Unix, and in the runtime libraries of most C compilers. See section POSIX Error Codes.


.RE
.B
\fBreturned_non_ip_address() ::\fR
\fB          {local, binary()} | {unspec, <<>>} | {undefined, any()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
a non-IP network address.

.PP
Addresses besides \fIip_address/0\fR ones that are returned from socket API functions. See in particular \fIlocal_address/0\fR. The \fIunspec\fR family corresponds to \fIAF_UNSPEC\fR and can occur if the other side has no socket address. The \fIundefined\fR family can only occur in the unlikely event of an address family that the VM doesn't recognize.


.RE
.B
\fBsocket() :: port() | module_socket().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
A socket recognized by this module and its siblings.

.PP
See \fIgen_tcp:socket/0\fR and \fIgen_udp:socket/0\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBsocket_address() ::\fR
\fB          ip_address() | any | loopback | local_address().\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBsocket_getopt() ::\fR
\fB          gen_sctp:option_name() |\fR
\fB          gen_tcp:option_name() |\fR
\fB          gen_udp:option_name().\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBsocket_optval() ::\fR
\fB          gen_sctp:option_value() |\fR
\fB          gen_tcp:option() |\fR
\fB          gen_udp:option() |\fR
\fB          gen_tcp:pktoptions_value().\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBsocket_protocol() :: tcp | udp | sctp.\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBsocket_setopt() ::\fR
\fB          gen_sctp:option() | gen_tcp:option() | gen_udp:option().\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
